		<hr />
		
		
		
		
		<div>I was playing with Japan on a random, huge map.  My closest neighbor was the Zulus, and as luck would have it we were the two most powerful nations in the world. After fighting them for about 3 centuries, and gaining the upper hand with my samurai armies we achieved peace (they had roughly 1/3rd of there cities left).  So I was the new superpower and was able to peacefully build until the 1950’s.  <br />
<br />
It was then, in the 50’s that I decided to attack the Russians on a tiny peninsula with two cities (Yakutsk and Grozny).  The Russians had been a diplomatic pain for many years and I was tired of it.  Plus, I wanted to finally get to use bombers, fighters, tanks, and artillery.  The limited war on the Yakutsk peninsula was easy.  The Russians were woefully lacking in technology and my allies, the Persians, even got in on the act.  It was then that this limited, simple war blew up.  The Indians (the new #2 civ) and the Egyptians declared an embargo on me.  The French joined the war effort with the Russians, and eventually they convinced the Zulu to declare war.  That worked well with me as the remaining Zulu cities were quickly mopped up.  Then the other continent got into the act and declared war against me.  The British (who were also strong) and the Iroquois decided to join the world war against the Persians and me.  <br />
<br />
Now I decided another ally might be useful so I got the Chinese to join the Japanese/Persian alliance.  Immediately the Egyptians declared war against us and began taking out Chinese cities.  The Persians quickly opted out (after some great battles defending against the Egyptians) and they immediately joined the attack on the Chinese.  By 1965 my war weariness was out of control and I had to abort my efforts against the Egyptians after gaining only two insignificant cities.  The Chinese were on their own and quickly fell to the Persian, Egyptian, Indian, Russian, French, British, and Iroquois.  I couldn’t really help them as the fighting had moved to the Eastern edge of the continent and was too far away for me to be of any use.<br />
<br />
The war concluded with the loss of two civilizations (Chinese and Zulu).  The Persians became a permanent friend of the Indians, so I lost my other ally as well.  The Egyptians started demanding more and more diplomatic “gifts” so by 1974 I had a vast army on their border and quickly captured every bit of territory they took from the Chinese (and then some).  I learned some valuable lessons.  First, a limited, quick war doesn’t always remain limited or quick.  Second, always watch the Indians (later I fought some huge wars with them).  Third, people in republics don’t hate war…they just hate long wars. It was a difficult war, but I have never had one that was quite as much fun as that one.</div>
	</td>
</tr>
